Dependency

This lesson talks about adding artifacts as Maven dependencies and their management, one of the most important features of Maven.

One of the tasks Maven excels at is handling dependencies for a given project. It can also handle transitive dependencies, which means if your project P depends on a jar A, which in turn depends on jar B, then Maven would download both the dependencies for you. In this case, jar A will be referred to as a direct dependency while jar B will be considered a transitive dependency for your project P. If jar B is in turn dependent on jar C, and jar C is in turn dependent on jar D, Maven will also download jars C and D when building your project P. Jars B, C, and D will collectively be called as transitive dependencies.

Maven can also resolve any dependency version conflicts and allow certain dependencies to be excluded. But how is Maven able to determine the complete set of dependencies for a given project? This is made possible by the POM file that is also installed for an artifact in the repository. Recall that the empty-project-1.jar artifact was installed in the local repository with the empty-project-1.pom file too. So now, if a new project takes a dependency on the empty-project.jar, Maven will be able to determine transitive dependencies using the empty-project-1.pom file and download dependencies for empty-project-1.jar too.

Let’s see a practical example of how dependencies are downloaded. We’ll add a dependency for a publicly available Google API client jar in the POM file and then run Maven. Follow the instructions in the widget below:

cd /Project18
# Now compute the dependency tree for the project. Since we have not added
# any dependency, the tree should be empty.
mvn dependency:tree -Dverbose
# Now add the following snippet after the <name> tag in the POM file
#
#    <dependencies>
#        <dependency>
#            <groupId>com.google.api-client</groupId>
#            <artifactId>google-api-client</artifactId>
#            <version>1.30.9</version>
#        </dependency>
#    </dependencies>
#
vi pom.xml
# Now recompute the dependency tree
mvn dependency:tree -Dverbose
# Next we'll install the project and verify Maven downloads transitive
# dependencies for us. But before we build the project we'll clean out
# any existing Google artifacts from our repository to be able to easily
# see the Google artifacts downloaded for this project by Maven.
rm -rf ~/.m2/repository/com/google/
mvn install
# You can examine the transitive dependencies Maven downloads to the local
# repo

The important take-away from the exercise is that Maven downloads transitive dependencies for us and it is able to do so using POM files associated with the artifacts. In the above exercise, the following dependency was added to the POM file. Subsequently, Maven downloaded dependencies of our dependency (transitive dependencies) to the local Maven repository.

        <dependency>
            <groupId>com.google.api-client</groupId>
            <artifactId>google-api-client</artifactId>
            <version>1.30.9</version>
        </dependency>

If you examine the associated POM file, it will list the following dependencies. These are also listed on Maven’s central repository here. The dependencies are categorized as being “test”, “compile”, and “provided”. We’ll cover what these mean in later chapters.

  <dependencies>
    <dependency>
      <groupId>com.google.oauth-client</groupId>
      <artifactId>google-oauth-client</artifactId>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
      <groupId>com.google.http-client</groupId>
      <artifactId>google-http-client-jackson2</artifactId>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
      <groupId>com.google.http-client</groupId>
      <artifactId>google-http-client-gson</artifactId>
      <scope>test</scope>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
      <groupId>com.google.http-client</groupId>
      <artifactId>google-http-client-protobuf</artifactId>
      <scope>test</scope>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
      <groupId>junit</groupId>
      <artifactId>junit</artifactId>
      <scope>test</scope>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
      <groupId>commons-codec</groupId>
      <artifactId>commons-codec</artifactId>
      <scope>provided</scope>
      <version>1.14</version>
   </dependency>
    <dependency>
      <groupId>com.google.guava</groupId>
      <artifactId>guava</artifactId>
    </dependency>
  </dependencies>

In the exercise, we used the command below to print the dependency tree for the artifact.

mvn dependency:tree -Dverbose

The command invokes the tree goal of the dependency plugin and the system property verbose is specified for a detailed output. The tree printed on the console consists of +- and \- and may appear confusing to read. Consider the dependency tree shown in the widget below copied from the exercise.

The plus \+ symbol indicates several nodes on the same level, while the \- symbol indicates one single node or the last node for that level of hierarchy. This will be clear once we go through the example above. The root of the tree is the first line, which is our project io.datajek:project18:jar:1. Immediately after the root is the artifact com.google.api-client:google-api-client:jar:1.30.9:compile which is a direct dependency that we added. The scope for the dependency is also printed. Note that this artifact starts with \-, implying that there’s only one node at the first level. This makes sense since we had a single dependency in our POM file. This artifact has three dependencies in turn:

  1. com.google.oauth-client:google-oauth-client:jar:1.30.5:compile

  2. com.google.http-client:google-http-client-jackson2:jar:1.34.2:compile

  3. com.google.guava:guava:jar:28.2-android:compile

Note the 1st and 2nd dependencies are listed with \+ symbol while the 3rd is listed with the \- symbol. All three dependencies are at the same level with the 3rd being the last notified by the \- symbol. Another way to visualize dependency trees and the \+ and \- symbols is as follows:

+- 1. first entry first level
|  +- 1.1 first entry second level
|  +- 1.2 second entry second level
|     \- 1.2.1 third level first and only entry
|  \- 1.3 third entry second level
|     \- 1.3.1 third level first and only entry
|        \- 1.3.1.1 fourth level first and only entry
+- 2. second entry first level
\- 3. last entry first level
   +- 3.1 second-last entry second level
   \- 3.2 last entry second level
